<emphasis id="B975EAFE09680B6EFC9DF92DFC1772BA" box="[815,927,1757,1783]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="106">P. viticola</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EF904B1D09680B6EFC15F92EFBDF72BA" author="Schaeffer, C. F. A." box="[935,1111,1757,1783]" pageId="14" pageNumber="106" pagination="325 - 352" refId="ref11952" refString="Schaeffer, C. F. A. (1908) List of the longicorn Coleoptera collected on the Museum expeditions to Brownsville, Texas and the Huachuca Mts., Arizona, with descriptions of new genera and species and notes on known species. Science Bulletin of the Museum of the Brooklyn Institute of Arts and Sciences, 1 (12), 325 - 352." type="journal article" year="1908">Schaeffer, 1908</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(see photographs of 
<typeStatus id="54BA884E09680B6EFAF7F92DFA0872B5" box="[1349,1408,1758,1784]" pageId="14" pageNumber="106">types</typeStatus>
at 
<bibRefCitation id="EF904B1D09680B6EFF25F8F2FEA07356" author="Bezark, L. G." box="[151,296,1793,1819]" pageId="14" pageNumber="106" refId="ref11405" refString="Bezark, L. G. (2019) A photographic Catalog of the Cerambycidae of the World. New World Cerambycidae Catalog. Available from: https: // apps 2. cdfa. ca. gov / publicApps / plant / bycidDB / wsearch. asp? w = n (accessed 15 March 2019)" type="url" year="2019">Bezark 2019</bibRefCitation>
) by the elytra being mostly black, with the elytral apex entirely light (in 
<taxonomicName id="4C014D6F09680B6EFBD0F8F1FB5A7356" authorityName="Schaeffer" authorityYear="1908" box="[1122,1234,1793,1819]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Pygmaeopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="106" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="viticola">
<emphasis id="B975EAFE09680B6EFBD0F8F1FB5A7356" box="[1122,1234,1793,1819]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="106">P. viticola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, mostly orangish, with irregular, moderately small dark areas interspersed, with the apical area not contrasting with the remaining surface), and the central area of the dorsal surface of the elytra without a narrow, longitudinal, fragmented pubescent band (present in 
<taxonomicName id="4C014D6F09680B6EFEE1F89DFE4A73CA" authorityName="Schaeffer" authorityYear="1908" box="[339,450,1901,1927]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Pygmaeopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="106" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="viticola">
<emphasis id="B975EAFE09680B6EFEE1F89DFE4A73CA" box="[339,450,1901,1927]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="106">P. viticola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), and by the antennomeres proportionally thicker.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BBE36EC09680B6EFF75F862FEF97382" blockId="14.[151,1437,1648,1999]" pageId="14" pageNumber="106">
<emphasis id="B975EAFE09680B6EFF75F862FEC073E6" bold="true" box="[199,328,1937,1963]" pageId="14" pageNumber="106">Etymology</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName id="4C014D6F09680B6EFEEAF861FDC673E6" authorityName="Bezark &amp; Santos-Silva" authorityYear="2019" box="[344,590,1937,1963]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Pygmaeopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="106" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apicalis">
<emphasis id="B975EAFE09680B6EFEEAF861FDC673E6" box="[344,590,1937,1963]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="106">Pygmaeopsis apicalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is named for the light-colored apical portion of the elytra which contrasts with the remainder.
</paragraph>
